---
title: "Bootstrapping a Self-Hosting Compiler"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-06
abstract: A self-hosting compiler presents the chicken-and-egg problem: how to bootstrap its own compilation process without relying on existing compilers. We outline our five-module bootstrap strategy and verify its correctness using formal properties.
---

# Introduction

We introduce the challenge of bootstrapping a self-hosting compiler, where the compiler's compilation process relies on itself for execution. This creates an inherent paradox: how can we create a compiler that compiles itself? Our solution involves dividing the bootstrap process into five modules, which we will discuss in detail.

## Section 1: Problem Statement

The chicken-and-egg problem arises from the need for both input files and a working compiler to execute them. Without a working compiler, it cannot compile anything; without compiled output, it cannot run the compiler.

// Example of a dependent function
fn egg(x: int) -> bool {
    return x == 0 || (x > 0 && egg(x - 1))
}

## Section 2: Module 1: Language Definition

Our first module focuses on defining the Lateralus language, including its syntax, semantics, and type system. This provides a foundation for the rest of the bootstrap process.

// Example of a typed function
type Int = nat
fn example(x: Int) -> Int {
    return x + 1
}

## Section 3: Module 2: Compilation

In this module, we implement the Lateralus compiler, which takes source code as input and produces executable machine code. We must ensure that the compilation process is correct and complete.

// Example of a compilation pass
fn compile(pass: Pass) -> Code {
    // Implement compilation logic here
    todo!(pass)
}

